    <text>
        <body>
      
		<pb n="1"/>
			<p><hi rend="underline">32 E</hi></p>
			<p rend="align(right)"><placeName>St. Louis</placeName>&#44; <date>January 6&#44; 1851</date>.</p>
			<p><addressee>Rev. Isaac Leeser</addressee>&#44; <placeName>Phila.</placeName></p>
			<p>Dear Sir&#58;</p>
          <p rend="indent(1)">I am missing your publication of the Occident and I don&#39;t<lb/> know what caused you to stop sending it to me.</p>
          <p rend="indent(1)">In an earlier letter I offered you a magnificent Sepher Torah<lb/> which I had in <placeName>New York</placeName> with <persName>Mr. Petschan</persName>&#44; to show you that I would<lb/> like to pay my debt to you for sold and unsold books of your<lb/> publishing company. I also had in mind to send my dues for your<lb/> Occident. However&#44; the struggle of a beginner who is fighting<lb/> for his mere existence&#44; as well as my insufficient speaking and<lb/> writing knowledge of the English language prevented me to do so.</p>
          <p rend="indent(1)">I had moreover the bad fortune to be cheated by <persName>Mr. DeYoung</persName><lb/> of <placeName>New York</placeName>. I have sold to <persName>Mr. DeYoung</persName>&#44; on <date>Rosh Ha&#45;Shana&#44; 1850</date>&#44;<lb/> an order of Sefarin and Tallith&#44; the whole for &#36;70. He gave me<lb/> &#36;10. cash and a money order for three months for &#36;60. I gave this<lb/> money order to my printer&#44; <persName>Mr. Muhlhauser</persName> in <placeName>New York</placeName>&#44; but he could<lb/> not cash it up to this day. In spite of my very small means and the<lb/> hardships&#44; and in spite of the fact that <persName>Mr. Muhlhauser</persName> did not<lb/> press for his money&#44; I paid him. I am anxious to fulfill my obligation<lb/> to you too and I would have done it long ago if it would have been<lb/> possible without endangering my young business. Some of your books<lb/> however&#44; are still unsold and some I have sold to people who have<lb/> not paid up to now.</p>
          <p rend="indent(1)">I therefore offer you the money order of <persName>Mr. DeYoung</persName>. You<lb/> knew him and trusted him&#44; with money affairs. <persName>Mr. Levy</persName>&#44; &#40;who has<lb/> a clothing store on <placeName>Chatham Street</placeName>&#41; vouches that he is honest and<lb/> that he would entrust him with &#36;500. &#40;The president of the congre&#45;<lb/>gation recommends him. This may be the same man as <persName>Mr. Levy</persName>. ESC&#41;<lb/> For several years <persName>Mr. DeYoung</persName> was also in charge of taking in the<lb/> money from the members of the Congregation&#44; which was one of the<lb/> reasons I gave him credit.</p>
          <p rend="indent(1)">I don&#39;t want you to buy the money order&#44; but to cause <persName>Mr.<lb/> DeYoung</persName> to cash it and you can deduct your amount &#40;321. according<lb/> to my book&#41; I also authorize you to settle with <persName>Mr. DeYoung</persName> as far<lb/> as time is concerned and if he wants to pay cash to accept even<lb/> &#36;40. instead of &#36;60. I would request only the surplus money over<lb/> &#36;21.</p>
          <p rend="indent(1)">With your honorable standing&#44; your acquaintance and your<lb/> influence&#44; you should have no trouble at all&#44; while neither I in<lb/> <placeName>St. Louis</placeName> nor my agent in <placeName><sic>NewYork</sic></placeName>&#44; can do a thing in this matter.<lb/> So if you have any prospect of getting the money&#44; you may use the<lb/> enclosed letter to <persName>Mr. Dornitzer</persName> to obtain the money order.</p>
          <p rend="indent(1)">Should you not wish to accept this offer then you may choose<lb/> and receive books of my publishing company for the same amount&#44; which<lb/> <persName>Mr. Petschan</persName> in <placeName>New York</placeName> has on consignment&#44; &#40;after <del>&#63;</del> deducting<lb/> 1&#47;3 discount from the list price.</p>
          <p rend="indent(1)">I hope that my offers will show you that I really mean to<lb/> pay as good as I can. Should your journal continue I would appreciate</p>
			<p rend="align(center)">over</p>
		<pb n="2"/>
			<p>your sending it to me. Eventually&#44; I would contribute an<lb/> article worthy of printing.</p>
          <p rend="indent(1)">Wishing you a happy and long life in noble action for<lb/> our brothers in faith.</p>
          <p rend="indent(3)">I am</p>
          <p rend="indent(4)">Cordially yours&#44;</p>
          <p rend="indent(5)"><persName role="author">ISIDOR BUSH</persName></p>
			<p rend="Addressed"><addressee>Mr. Isaac Leeser</addressee>&#44; Editor of the Occident&#44; etc. etc.<lb/> <placeName>Philadelphia&#44; Pa.</placeName></p>
			<p rend="Enclosure">Letter addressed to <persName>Mr. H. Dornister</persName>&#44; <placeName>New York&#44; Cigar Store<lb/> 165 Canal Street</placeName>&#44;<lb/> requesting him to turn over note for &#36;60. of <persName>Mr. DeYoung</persName> to <persName>Mr. Isaac<lb/> Leeser</persName>.</p>
			<p><add><persName>Leeser</persName>&#44; evidently&#44; did not care to collect <persName role="author">Bush&#39;s</persName> debt in<lb/> this way.</add></p>

          
